Hello Bill,



&gt;&gt; I&#39;m not certain t=
hat today&#39;s JAX-RS offers much more than today&#39;s WCF
in 
&gt;&gt; terms of REST s=
upport. If Glenn&#39;s team are going to do &quot;REST like
they 
&gt;&gt; meant it&quot; to pa=
raphrase Guilherme, I don&#39;t think that JAX-RS is the 
&gt;&gt; right way to go.
&gt;=

&gt; But that&#39;s just an opinion. Or is there some technical criticism as
wel=
l?

It&#39;s an opinion - I don&#39;t have any carefully gathered empirical evidenc=
e
to back it up. However both WCF and JAX-RS avoid hypermedia which is
pret=
ty important for RESTful solutions. In other bits of that email, I
pointed =
out that some JAX-RS compliant frameworks (e.g. Jersey) are now
experimenti=
ng with hypermedia which makes them much more useful if the
abstractions co=
me out right.

In terms of technical critique, I think JAX-RS comes out ahe=
ad of WCF
because it&#39;s marginally easier to TDD with it, and so much more o=
f the
framework is above the waterline rather than buried down deep. Howeve=
r
at this point both frameworks are simply nicer programmatic interfaces
at=
op a Web server, and both short-change client-side developers (with
JAX-RS =
again being better than WCF).

Since neither has hypermedia support from th=
e start, retrofitting it at
this point may result in horrid abstractions. T=
hat&#39;s why I&#39;m broadly
supportive of Glenn&#39;s outreach and very supportive of=
 the people behind
Restfulie (as well as being encouraged by the steps the =
Jersey team are
taking).

Jim











